label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Resilience Lab | Late Night]

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, slow cello; the tempo of a tide pulling away]
    "You stand at the bench with your palms flat on the laminated plans. The ink has bled where rain tracked through your coat earlier; someone—Noah Ríos, you think—has left a coffee ring that looks like a"
    "rough topography of the bay. The lab smells of wet earth and metal: compost, brine, the sharp copper tang of exposed connectors. Your jacket still smells faintly of Elena's lemon oil from the shop, as if"
    "that small, stubborn scent could anchor the whole place."
    "Noah Ríos is hunched over a tablet, blue light sketching across his face. His brass identification band catches the lamp as he turns; a small, ordinary flare that steadies you more than it should. He speaks before you can file the plans away."
    show noah_ros at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ros "They're in. Partial grants. Phased, conditional—reinforced composites for the foundation, denser anchors, that sort of thing. Arman Kade's donors put the money on the table the minute we agreed to the specification language he wanted."
    "You let the sentence settle like a stone thrown into a pond; the ripples are already wider than you can measure."
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "The composites—how much did they change the plan?"

    "Noah Ríos [observing] (his thumb tracing a line on the schematic)" "The terraced mats get reduced. Less soil mass, fewer planted pockets near the base. We keep the public promenade, technically, but the terraces are slimmer. Anchor spacing is denser. It buys structural redundancy, but it's... less living. It's engineered to hold the shore for the next surge, not to regrow it."

    mara_evans "Less living.' The words taste of salt and apology. 'So—people stay, at least for now."
    "Noah Ríos looks up, searching your face for the steadiness he thinks he sees but worries he can't always count on."

    noah_ros "We reduce immediate erosion rates. Cass gets the breathing room she needs at City Council. We can show numbers, show a pilot that works before the next storm season. That—"
    "You cut him off because your throat tightens. 'That was the ask. The ask was to keep people here. Not to make a version of it that only looks like home.'"

    noah_ros "I know. I know. I'm trying to make both things—proof we can scale, and proof that the community isn't erased."
    "You hold onto the edge of the workbench until your knuckles ache. The lab hums around you; pumps in the back ripple like muted applause. You think of Elena's face when she read the building notice—worry"
    "that was edged with a quick, hard grin she uses when she wants to look brave. You think of Tomas's hands, moving with the patience of someone who has mended more than nets."

    noah_ros "There were arguments. I pushed. Priya pushed models that showed the composites kept a lot of the wave energy from translating into catastrophic bed drop. Arman Kade drove the funding conversation; the donors were clear—'no experimental deep-beds unless it's partially guaranteed.'"

    mara_evans "So we sell some of the experiment for guarantees."

    noah_ros "We did what we had to, Mara."
    "An ugly little sound—half-laugh, half-anger—escapes you. It isn't judgment; it is the friction of grief rubbing against necessity."

    menu:
        "Ask Noah to tell you exactly what was cut":
            "Noah leans in, names the terraces and the soil volume, the changes in planting schedule. Detail doesn't make the loss smaller, but it lets you name it."
        "Step outside for air and put your face to the rain":
            "You push through the door into moist night. Rain tastes like metal. For a moment you let yourself be a small, angry vessel—isolated, pulsing—before you fold back in and listen."

    # --- merge ---
    "The conversation resumes with Noah outlining compromise options and phased approaches."

    noah_ros "I argued we could phase composites with later retrofit pockets for matting—"

    mara_evans "You argued?"

    noah_ros "I argued hard. But investors wanted a predictable load path. They want figures they can show to other cities—'it held for X gusts, prevented Y cubic meters of loss.' It's not that they don't care, Mara. They care about different things."

    mara_evans "Different things."

    noah_ros "I don't like what we cut any more than you do. But if we don't get this done—get the pilot under way—Arman Kade rolls in with the big wall and the displacement plan, and the community loses legal standing to argue at all."
    "The room tilts. He lays a hand on the schematic, over one of the terrace nodes, as if he can press the promise back into being."
    "You sit down on the bench because your legs forget how to keep you upright. The lab is suddenly too bright, all its ordinary equipment exposed like witnesses."

    mara_evans "Did Elena say yes?"

    noah_ros "She keeps the shop. Reduced frontage, a consortium-managed cal zone for deliveries—it's complicated. She took the offer so she could keep a presence. Tomas—"

    mara_evans "Tomas?"

    noah_ros "He's mending nets tonight, alone. He accepted the community council's stipend for elder maintenance. He said he wants to keep teaching the kids the old currents. But—' his voice falters; the information is both public and private. 'He looks different. Like some of his horizon has been boxed in."
    "You fold the corner of a printout between your fingers until it creases. The lab's low light becomes a halo around Noah Ríos's jaw."

    noah_ros "We can add the sensors as we promised. If the tech proves out, we can attract more funding for the retrofit—more living pockets later. We scale sensor arrays into adjacent cities as a package; the donor's network will buy that story. It makes our model replicable."
    "You swallow. The word 'replicable' tastes like antiseptic."

    mara_evans "And us?"
    "Noah Ríos studies you like someone reading a map of an old town that has been altered by new streets."

    noah_ros "You anchor the living design in the pilot phase. I... I take the sensor program and push it into deployment. We make the technical case. That gives you leverage later—evidence, models, allies. It means the work continues."

    mara_evans "It means I stay to hold the thread here, while you take the clean, predictable thing into other places."

    noah_ros "It means I finally prove the tech is good enough that donors will fund the retrofit we both want. It means I don't get crushed by this same argument again."
    "Your chest tightens until the pendant at your throat seems to be the only thing keeping your ribs from floating away. You think about what proof—numbers, graphs, buoy logs—can bring and what hands and terraces and"
    "warm, living soil bring. You think about the child who pressed a kelp frond into your palms and how small and vital that frond felt."
    hide noah_ros
    hide mara_evans

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Cello drops to a single, slow note]
    show noah_ros at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ros "I'm not asking you to be okay with it, Mara. I'm asking you to trust that this is one way to keep people here who might otherwise be moved."
    "You look at him. He looks tired in a way that makes your insides ache; beneath his pragmatism there is a rawness you know well—fear that he'll be seen as a technician first and a neighbor second."
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "I don't know if trust can be engineered."

    noah_ros "Maybe not. But trust isn't the only thing that builds things."
    "The words hang. The plan is crystalline and compromised—sound for the moment, hollow in the places you loved most."
    hide noah_ros
    hide mara_evans

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft sustained tone, then cut]
    # [Scene: Community Space | Midday — Pilot Presentation]

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Muffled chatter, the scrape of chairs, the occasional gull through the open door]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low ambient—heartbeat synth beneath community murmurs]
    "You stand at the front of the room, your notes in your hand like a talisman. Priya's simulations scroll behind you: color-coded maps, predicted sediment retention, probability cones for storm events. Cass sits at the side,"
    "impeccable and human in the way that surprises you—her sea-glass brooch catching the light like a small promise."
    show mara_evans at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "This first phase is designed to stop immediate erosion, to protect ground-level access along the main promenade and to demonstrate structural durability for the council. It uses reinforced composites at the base and denser anchors so we can show a measurable reduction in erosion within the first year."
    "A murmur. Someone in the third row—an older woman you know—raises her hand."

    "Resident" "Will we still be able to fish off the pier? My family's boat is—"

    mara_evans "Yes. Access points are preserved in the plan. We prioritized public ramps at the main nodes. The piloting measures will not close the promenade."

    "A man near the back, voice crackling with exhaustion" "You said 'prioritized'—does that mean they can be taken away later?"

    mara_evans "The pilot includes legal easements that protect key access points for the community. Priya's models are part of an evidence package we'll give City Council to make those easements binding."
    show cassandra_cass_green at right:
        zoom 0.7

    cassandra_cass_green "This buys time on a political scale. It prevents an immediate lockout and gives us the window we need to negotiate stronger, longer-term protections."
    "You watch faces in the room: hope, calculation, relief, suspicion. Elena stands at the back with paint-flecked overalls and a bandanna, smiling small and uterine with worry. Tomas sits closer to the front, hands folded on his knees, his gaze somewhere beyond the room."
    show tomas_belmar at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_belmar "If the water keeps coming like it did when I was a boy, we'll need more than promises. But this—this will stop some of the fast things. It gives my granddaughter a place to go home to in the immediate future."

    mara_evans "Is that enough?"

    tomas_belmar "Enough keeps people breathing. It's not whole. But enough is something to pass on."
    "You nod because his answer is not a solution you can design for; it's a human measure, rough and precise in its own way."

    menu:
        "Invite Tomas to help design the retrofit phase":
            "He squints, then cracks a rare half-smile. He says yes, because the idea of teaching the retrofit to young hands steadies him."
        "Promise the room you'll keep fighting for living terraces":
            "You make the promise. It lands like a promise always does—lubricated by sincerity but heavy with the weight of compromise you already signed onto."

    # --- merge ---
    "The presentation concludes and volunteers move to distribute soup; private conversations follow."
    "Later, at the civic table outside where volunteers hand out hot soup, Elena pulls you aside. She smells of oil and citrus; her hands are rough but kind."
    hide mara_evans
    show elena_torres at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_torres "I keep the storefront. They cut off a bit of the frontage but it's still mine. I can still paint the signs. But they'll put a loading zone there and the rent's... they managed to wedge it so the small businesses breathe, for now."
    hide cassandra_cass_green
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "You're still there?"

    elena_torres "For now. I got to promise the kids I'll keep the shop open. I couldn't say no."
    "You hold her hands because they are familiar and stubborn. You want to brag about the legal easements and the pilot's evidence, to name the numbers that will mean the world for Cass in chambers next week, but the thing that matters to Elena is the front door."

    mara_evans "We'll keep fighting for more. The retrofit plan—retrofits are possible later. We can push donors toward funding the living components if the pilot proves the need."

    elena_torres "Promise me you'll still put green things in the front when you can, yeah?"

    mara_evans "I promise."
    "Her hand squeezes back. It is a small, human confirmation against all the spreadsheets and compromise."
    hide tomas_belmar
    hide elena_torres
    hide mara_evans

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Understated strings—melancholic, resigned]
    # [Scene: East Strand Pier | Night — After the Vote]

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The steady breathing of the bay; distant traffic, the creak of timbers]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Distant piano, slow and small]
    "You walk out with the hydrophone slung in its canvas bag. The pilot has the money. Cass can breathe. Elena still paints her signs. Tomas is counting on you to keep teaching. The list of small,"
    "human victories is long enough to make your chest ache and short enough to hurt."
    "You slip the hydrophone out and set it to the surface. The recorder lights a faint red. You listen—not for numbers, this time, but for the sound the bay makes when it knows decisions have been made in its name."
    "The sound is low and patient: a raw chord under everything, like a held breath turned into water. You press your forehead to the cold metal of the buoy and close your eyes. The sound wraps around old losses and new promises."
    "A message pings on your phone—a short line from Noah Ríos."
    show noah_ros at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ros "I'm boarding a flight tomorrow. Donor meeting in the morning. They want the sensor kit demo with the pilot in a month. Could mean other cities too. Can we talk?"
    "You rub the pendant at your throat and type with fingers that feel like someone else's."
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "Meet me at the pier. One hour."
    "He is already there when you look up. His breath fogs in the night; his jacket smells like the inside of the lab and a faint, clean trace of aviation fuel. He does not try to fix the bay's sound. He stands beside you and listens."

    noah_ros "They like the numbers. They like the sensor story. They want to scale. They can fund the next phase if the pilot proves the sensors decouple the insurance risk."

    mara_evans "So you go. You take the clean city story and make it work, and the retrofit becomes possible later."

    noah_ros "Yes. I can go. I can push for retrofit funding if the tech makes the case. But I'd be lying if I said I wasn't… terrified, not about failing the tech, but about us. About what it means to split the work."
    "You turn the hydrophone toward the dark."

    mara_evans "Do you want me to come?"

    noah_ros "You have East Strand to anchor. I… would not be the person I am if I didn't try to make the tech undeniable. If I can sell this in three other cities, donors will have to fund retrofit pockets. It makes the living design more possible politically."

    mara_evans "And if they don't?"

    noah_ros "Then this pilot—this compromise—was only a delay. It'll buy breath, but not the future you want."
    "You both look at the bounded pool of light on the water. The city feels slightly larger and smaller all at once."

    noah_ros "We could be in different places for a while. I—' He hesitates, and you hear the human calculus behind his words. 'I don't know how to make it not feel like abandoning."

    "Mara Evans (after a long suffocation of silence)" "Neither do I. But choosing to stay isn't the same as staying the same."
    "He searches your face as if translating your expression into coordinates. He reaches across and takes your hand—an old habit of his when words risked becoming too brittle. His fingers are warm."

    noah_ros "Promise me you'll call if the donors start pushing for more immediate, non-negotiable cutbacks. Promise me you'll say no to the parts that shutter access. I'll promise to push the retrofit fund harder if the pilot proves the tech."

    mara_evans "I promise—I'll hold them to it. But I can't promise the outcome."

    noah_ros "And I can't promise to be here tomorrow night."
    "His thumb strokes your knuckles once. The gesture is small and intimate and utterly practical: a human link between two strategies."

    mara_evans "Then we'll keep making promises that are true as far as they go."
    "You both stand there with the bay's patient chord humming beneath your feet. The pilot will begin. The grants will arrive. Cass will have time, and Elena will keep painting signs, and Tomas will teach the"
    "kids how to read the currents. And yet the terraces you loved are smaller on paper than in your memory; the living things you wanted woven into concrete are postponed to a later time that, while"
    "hope-filled, is not certain."
    hide noah_ros
    hide mara_evans

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Single piano note fades into the sound of the water]
    "You fold the plan into your notebook and put the kelp frond Elena pressed into your palm inside its pages. There is a neat crease where the paper meets plant; the green will fade, but the imprint remains."
    "You walk back toward the lab with Noah Ríos's hand briefly in yours; it is a warmth that does not erase the ache. The pilot is a victory and a wound—a proof that something can be"
    "kept, and a proof that keeping it will require patience and more negotiation than you had imagined."
    "At the edge of the pier, Tomas lights a small lantern and sets it bobbing on the water. A slow procession of small lights answers—neighbors keeping vigil with the things they can offer: lamps, cups, songs."
    "It is a fragile parade against the dark and, for the moment, that fragility is enough."
    "You touch your pendant and let the weight of it steady the small, complicated truth you will carry: you saved much. You traded away parts you loved to keep those who could not leave. You did"
    "not hand the neighborhood over to Arman Kade—this matter. But the shore you are protecting is not the one you first dreamed of."
    "You close your notebook and look at Noah Ríos. He looks back with the same worn, gentle resolve you see in your own reflection."
    show mara_evans at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "We are protected, but not whole."
    hide mara_evans

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Slow strings, carrying a bittersweet resonance — a melody that resolves downward rather than upward]
    "You breathe in the salt and the diesel and the soft smoke from community fires. You let yourself feel the seams: relief braided with loss, the sharpness of compromise tucked into the dull, steady work ahead."
    "You will return to the lab, to hearings, to petitions, to retrofit plans that may or may not find favor. You will also open the shop door with Elena when the morning comes, and you will"
    "listen to Tomas teach the kids how to tie a knot that holds in the worst of tides."
    "The city has bought a calendar of time, and time is something you both wanted and feared. The pilot is set. The sensors will hum. The living terraces will wait—promised, delayed, made contingent on numbers that are good but not everything."
    "You walk away holding the small, human proofs you have gathered: a kelp frond pressed flat, a legal easement filed with Cass's signature, a sensor prototype that will soon be boxed and sent to places you may never visit."
    "You are tired and quietly proud and hollowed at the same time."

    scene bg ch7_601bcb_9 at full_bg
